FIX: ModelViews can have Resources whose models have unique fields.ReadModelMixin and UpdateModelMixin store model instance as a property. This allows ModelResource to bind the ModelForm using the model instance making the form validate the input data against the model instance and not a brand new instance. When the latter happened and the model used unique fields, the form validation failed whenever a PUT was maintaining the previuos value of the unique field.n

Fix the tests on 1.3 and HEADIn the latest Django master code, RequestFactory.put behaves fundamentally differently than it did pre-1.5.  By default, it expects an octet string as opposed to a dictionary that it will encode like a multipart form.  So, for 1.5 and on, we have to be explicit about the multipart type and pre-encode the data.  However, pre-1.5 Django expects a dictionary if the content type is multipart.  So, the cleanest thing to do is explicitly handle the versions independently.n

Renderer negotiation: media_type specificty evaluation weakThe `DefaultContentNegotiation` handler usesrnrnFor example: Google Chrome sends an Accept-header of `Accept:text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8`, when I request a *.png URL.rnAfter matching the media-types with the available renderers (in my case only a custom `PNGRenderer` with a `media_type='image/png'`), only `*/*;q=0.8` is left, which happens to have the same length as the image/png media-type defined by the renderer (9 characters).rnrnThe specificity of the renderer's media-type over the Accept-header's one is only determined by length.rnUsing your `_MediaType.precedence` would be preferable in my eyes.rnrnRegards, Fabianrn

Add timedelta encoder to the JSONEncoder class.Whilst this commit adds *encoding* of timedeltas to a string of a floatingnpoint value of the seconds, you must add your own serializer field fornwhatever timedelta model field you are using. This is because Django doesn'tnsupport any kind of timedelta field out-of-the-box, so you have to eithernimplement your own or use django-timedelta.nnIf this is the case and you want to serialise timedelta input, you will havento implement your own special field to use for the timedelta, which is notnincluded in core as it is based on a 3rd party library. Here is an example:nnimport datetimenimport timedeltanfrom django import formsnfrom django.core import validatorsnfrom django.core.exceptions import ValidationErrornfrom django.utils.translation import ugettext_lazy as _nfrom rest_framework.fields import WritableFieldnnclass TimedeltaField(WritableField):ntype_name = 'TimedeltaField'nform_field_class = forms.FloatFieldnndefault_error_messages = {n'invalid': _('%s' value must be in seconds.),n}nndef from_native(self, value):nif value in validators.EMPTY_VALUES:nreturn Nonenntry:nreturn datetime.timedelta(seconds=float(value))nexcept (TypeError, ValueError):nmsg = self.error_messages['invalid'] % valuenraise ValidationError(msg)nnWhich is based on the FloatField. This field can then be used innyour serializer like this:nnfrom yourapp.fields import TimedeltaFieldnnclass YourSerializer(serializers.ModelSerializer):nduration = TimedeltaField()n

Fix default values always being False for browsable APIThis fixes a bug that was introduced in 28ff6fb [1] for thenbrowsable API, specifically with how it handled default valuesnfor boolean fields.  Previously, it had a global default fornboolean fields set to `False`, which was different than thenstandard None that was used elsewhere.  Because this only needednto be done for the browsable API, a fix was put into place thatnonly set the default to `False` when form data was passed intonthe serializer.  This had the unintended side effect of overridingnany default set on the boolean field.nnThis fixes #1101 [2] by only overriding the default if the default isn`None`, which is the default for all fields.nn[1]: https://github.com/tomchristie/django-rest-framework/commit/28ff6fb1ec02b7a04c4a0db54885f3735b6dd43fn[2]: https://github.com/tomchristie/django-rest-framework/issues/1101n

Allow viewset to specify lookup value regex for routingThis patch allows a viewset to define a pattern for its lookup field, which the router will honor. Without this patch, any characters are allowed in the lookup field, and overriding this behavior requires subclassing router and copying and pasting the implementation of get_lookup_regex.nnIt's possible it would be better to remove this functionality from the routers and simply expose a parameter to get_lookup_regex which allows overriding the lookup_regex. That way the viewset config logic could be in the a subclass, which could invoke the super method directly.nnI'm using this now for PostgreSQL UUID fields using https://github.com/dcramer/django-uuidfield . Without this patch, that field passes the lookup string to the database driver, which raises a DataError to complain about the invalid UUID. It's possible the field ought to signal this error in a different way, which could obviate the need to specify a pattern.n

Router: Do not automatically adjust lookup_regex when trailing_slash is TrueBREAKING CHANGEnnWhen trailing_slash is set to True, the router no longer will adjust the lookup regex to allow it to include periods. To simulate the old behavior, the programmer should specify `lookup_regex = '[^/]+'` on the viewset.nnhttps://github.com/tomchristie/django-rest-framework/pull/1328#issuecomment-31517099n

Refactor login template to extend base.While experimenting with extending DRF, I found that the login pagen1) had no title, and 2) duplicated <head> info from base.html.nnThis change adds a new {% block body %} to the base.html templatenwhich allows override of the entire html <body>. login_base.htmlnhas its duplicated head info stripped, and now extends base.htmlnto share common html <head> templating.nnAs part of this change, pretify.css is unnecessarily added tonlogin_base.html.  If this is deemed a problem, it will be easy tonblock that css out, and have login_base.html override the block.nnIdeally, I would have liked to create a new api_base.html that extendsnbase.html, move the api specific logic into that template, and leavenbase.html content agnostic, to truely be a unifying base for all DRFnpages.  But this change would break current apps that overridenapi.html and expect base.html to be the immediate super template. :/nnThis change is benificial because it:n - removes duplication of header declarations (mostly css includes)n - adds a html title to the login pagen - standardizes html header info across all DRF pagesnnDocs are updated to reflect the new structure.n

Leave status responsibility to parent classDjango's `HttpResponse` class checks for the `status` param when it'sninitialized, if it's `None` it uses the class attributen`status_code` and thanks to that we can do things like:nn```nclass BadRequest(HttpResponse):nstatus_code = 400n```nnNow, that doesn't work when inheriting from rest-framework's `Response`:nn```nclass BadRequest(rest_framework.response.Response):nstatus_code = 400  # Bad, it's always ignoredn```nnBecause a default status of `200` is being specified inn`rest_framework.response.Response`. I think is more Django-friendly tonjust leave that status default value to `None` and leave thenresponsibility of choosing its value to the parent class: `HttpResponse`.n

Update authentication.mdBased on the [new documentation](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/topics/auth/customizing/#django.contrib.auth.get_user_model) for Django 1.7 we should now use:rnrn```pythonrn@receiver(post_save, sender=settings.AUTH_USER_MODEL)rn```rninstead of:rnrn```python rn@receiver(post_save, sender=get_user_model())rn```rnbecause `get_user_model()` only works once Django has imported all models. Otherwise you'll get: rnrn```pythonrndjango.core.exceptions.AppRegistryNotReady: Models aren't loaded yet.rn```rnWhen trying to start your sever after adding token authentication.rnrnFrom the Docs, ( linked above as well ) :rn>New in Django 1.7:rn>When connecting to signals sent by the User model, you should specify the custom model using the AUTH_USER_MODEL setting.

Allow no queryset when get_queryset overriddenThe user may wish to provide a dynamic queryset on a `RelatedField`nbased on the `context`. The way to do that is to create a subclass ofn`RelatedField` (or a child) and override the `get_queryset` method.nHowever, this is undocumented, and instantiating that field without an`queryset` argument (because it's not needed) will raise an assertionnerror.nnDocument `.get_queryset(self)` as an official part of the API ofn`RelatedField`, and don't enforce the use of `queryset` whenn`get_queryset` is overridden.n

Upgrade transifex-client dependency to 0.11Version 0.11b3's setup.py had an undeclared dependency on `py2exe` whennrunning on Windows (seenhttps://github.com/transifex/transifex-client/blob/0.11b3/setup.py#L23),nwhich made it impossible to install without having a working `py2exe` tonbegin with.nnThis has been fixed in 0.11 proper.n

Upgrade isort to 4.2.2.This gets rid of a file encoding bug that occurs on Windows boxes wherenthe default implied encoding is cp1252, but the files themselves aren't.nnThe actual patch that seems to fix this isnhttps://github.com/timothycrosley/isort/commit/1057d5e12edbb3030045b7a7a8c82f0848635fefnbut it seems like a good idea to upgrade to the latest and greatest.n
Add `types` to isort's standard library list.This re-stabilizes sorting after upgrading to 4.2.2.n

Fix `smart_repr()` to also clean upper-case hex addresses.Windows Pythons seem to like printing addresses in upper-case, while LinuxnPythons like lower-case hexes.nnThis led to an amusing (for a given value of amusing, anyway) situationnwhere some repr tests would fail if the objects they were testing happenednto be allocated at an address with a hex digit in the range A..F.n

Updated NestedBoundField to also handle empty string when rendering its formIf a NestedBoundField field has a value of `None` and is inside another NestedBoundField field, it will have its value converted to an empty string while the form of its enclosing field is being rendered. So, NestedBoundField fields with an empty string value must be handled the same way as NestedBoundField fields with a `None` value.

Don't filter out the DecimalValidator if it is not supportedPreviously, all validators set on a DecimalField in Django would benstripped when converted to a Django REST framework field. However, if get_serializer()rnthrows an APIException (e.g. PermissionDenied), it doesn't get caught atrnthe call site, but instead propagates up and aborts the entire view.rnWith the try/except in this commit, the documentation generator insteadrngratiously ignores that particular view and moves on to the next onerninstead. SchemaJSRenderer renders invalid Javascript (#5607)* SchemaJSRenderer renders invalid JavascriptrnrnUnder Py3 the base64.b64encode() method returns a binary object, which gets rendered as `b'...'` in schema.js. This results in the output becoming:rnrnvar coreJSON = window.atob('b'eyJf...'');rnrnwhich is invalid Javascript. Because base64 only uses ASCII characters it is safe to decode('ascii') it. Under Py2 this will result in a unicode object, which is fine. Under Py3 it results in a string, which is also fine. This solves the problem and results in a working schema.js output.rnrn* Add regression test for #5608rnrn* Add regression test for #5608rnrn* Apparently the linter on Travis wants the imports in a different order than on my box...rn

The `name` may be overridden by providingrnit as an argument to the decorator.rnrnThe `get_view_name` and `get_view_description` hooks now provide thernview instance to the handler, instead of the view class. Add support for pagination in OpenAPI response schemas (#6867)Refs #6846rnrnThis provides a way for pagination classes to add pagination properties (`count`, `next`, `results` etc.) to OpenAPI response schemas.rnrnA new method `get_paginated_response_schema()` has been added to `BasePagination`. This method is intended to mirror `get_paginated_response()` (which takes a `list` and wraps it in a `dict`). rnrnHence, `get_paginated_response_schema()` takes an unpaginated response schema (of type `array`) and wraps that with a schema object of type `object` containing the relevant properties that the pagination class adds to responses.rnrnThe default implementation of `BasePagination.get_paginated_response_schema()` simply passes the schema through unmodified, for backwards compatibility.
